INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd44d4cf8-aff9-40d3-b0bf-82acc07d3263',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$ONNX Runtime + Feature Stores — Eliminating Training-Serving Skew at Inference$escape$,
  $escape$Training-serving skew is the silent killer of ONNX model performance. Your offline features (Parquet, Delta Lake) go through sklearn pipelines during training — but at inference, your online store (Redis, DynamoDB via Feast/Tecton) must produce byte-identical tensors to what ONNX Runtime expects.

Start by inspecting your model's contract: `session.get_inputs()` returns each input's `name`, `shape`, and `type` (e.g., `tensor(float)`). These names must exactly match what your feature store serves — no silent column renames allowed.

The fix: export your preprocessing pipeline as a separate ONNX graph using `sklearn-onnx` or `tf2onnx`, then chain it with your main model via `onnxruntime` session chaining or merge both into a single graph with `onnx.compose.merge_models`. Now both offline and online paths run the identical ONNX preprocessing graph — skew becomes structurally impossible.

For online latency, pin your `InferenceSession` with `ExecutionMode.ORT_SEQUENTIAL` and pre-allocate `numpy` buffers per feature vector shape. Avoid re-allocating on every request; feature stores return consistent shapes per entity type.$escape$,
  $escape$import onnxruntime as ort
import numpy as np

session = ort.InferenceSession("chained_model.onnx", providers=["CPUExecutionProvider"])
expected = {i.name: i.shape for i in session.get_inputs()}

# Fetch online features (Feast example)
fv = store.get_online_features(
    features=["user_stats:click_rate", "user_stats:session_count"],
    entity_rows=[{"user_id": uid}]
).to_dict()

feed = {
    name: np.array([[fv[name][0]]], dtype=np.float32)
    for name in expected
}
output = session.run(None, feed)[0]$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
